# AI OS

### The context layer between you and Claude

Most people start every AI conversation from zero. AI OS fixes that.

It's a structured prompt I built to give Claude persistent context about how I think, what I'm working on, and how I want to be challenged — so I don't spend the first 10 messages re-explaining myself every time I open a new chat.

The document maps five layers: identity, communication style, current priorities, daily constraints, and hard rules. Together they function like a system prompt for my own workflow — the difference between Claude giving me generic output and Claude operating like a thinking partner who already knows my context.

One document. Paste once. Every conversation starts where it should.

---

## Understanding Claude's Key Features

Before building your AI OS, it helps to understand how Claude is structured — and which features make persistent context possible.

---

### Claude

Claude is an AI assistant built by Anthropic. It's designed to reason, write, analyze, and problem-solve across almost any domain — from strategy documents to code to creative work.

Unlike a search engine, Claude doesn't retrieve information — it generates responses based on context. That's why **what you put in the conversation matters**. The more context you give, the more useful the output.

> **Example:** Asking "write a product brief" gets a generic template. Asking "write a product brief for a B2B SaaS targeting operations teams, using direct language and no corporate jargon" gets something you can actually use.

---

### Projects

Projects are Claude's way of giving you a persistent workspace. Instead of starting fresh in every conversation, a Project lets you:

- Store background context that Claude always has access to
- Upload files (docs, spreadsheets, briefs) Claude can reference in any chat
- Set custom instructions that apply to every conversation in that project

Think of a Project as a dedicated assistant who already read your company wiki before your first meeting.

> **Example:** You create a project called "Product Strategy." You upload your roadmap, your team's OKRs, and your AI OS. Now every conversation in that project starts with Claude already knowing your priorities, your constraints, and how you like to work.

---

### Instructions

Instructions are the rules you set for how Claude should behave — its tone, format, constraints, and boundaries — applied automatically to every conversation.

You can set instructions at the Project level (applies to all chats in that project) or globally (applies everywhere).

This is the core of the AI OS concept: instead of re-explaining yourself every time, you define your preferences once and Claude follows them by default.

> **Example instructions:**
> - "Always respond in bullet points unless I ask for prose."
> - "Don't start responses with 'Great question!' or affirmations."
> - "When I share an idea, challenge it before validating it."

---

### Artifacts

Artifacts are standalone outputs Claude generates that live in a dedicated side panel — separate from the chat. They're designed for content you want to keep, copy, or iterate on without it getting buried in the conversation.

Artifacts can be:
- **Documents** — briefs, reports, plans
- **Code** — scripts, functions, full files
- **HTML pages** — interactive tools or mockups rendered directly in the browser
- **SVG graphics** — diagrams and visual assets

> **Example:** You ask Claude to build a competitor analysis table. Instead of pasting it into the chat, Claude creates an Artifact — a clean, copyable document that stays visible on the right side of the screen while you continue the conversation.

---

### Skills

Skills are pre-built capabilities that extend what Claude can do beyond text generation. They allow Claude to take actions, use tools, or follow structured workflows — not just respond.

Depending on the platform and plan, Skills can include:

- **Web search** — look up current information in real time
- **Code execution** — run and test code, not just write it
- **File analysis** — read and extract data from uploaded documents
- **Integrations** — connect to external tools and services

> **Example:** Instead of asking Claude to estimate a market size from memory, you enable web search as a skill. Claude pulls current data, synthesizes it, and gives you a grounded answer — not a hallucinated one.

